[3] Brazil and Venezuela: Yanomami indigenous people
Date: Thu 05 Jul 2018
Source: Aporrea [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.aporrea.org/actualidad/n327646.html


A devastating measles epidemic is plaguing the indigenous community Yanomami in the Amazon, Venezuela border with Brazil, because of isolation, and precarious living conditions of families of this ethnic group.

Since March [2018], there are reports of indigenous sickened by the outbreak of measles, and the total number of people affected is unknown.

Yanomami Indians approached Wataniba, a socio-environmental working group of the Amazon, to share their concern and alarm regarding the epidemic prevailing in the communities of Alto Ocamo - Parima in Venezuela, in the region of Onkiola, the Brazilian side. The alarm is significant given the epidemiological vulnerability of people in front of this disease.

The 1st warning came from members of the Yanomami organization Hutukara, settled in Brazil who in March 2018 reported by radio to Yanomami health personnel in Chalbaud Delgado, there were sick people with measles in the sector "Hokomawe and Momoi" a region for members of the Yanomami Hutukara organization, which covers a large area of more than 11 communities in Venezuela and as many in Brazil. The Venezuelan side includes towns like Tokori, Hokomawë I, Hokomawë II, Koaiampu I, Koaiampu II, III Koaiampu, Irotha and Oroshi, all difficult to access.

Then they learned that 23 Yanomami arrived at a hospital in Boa Vista, the capital of Roraima state in Brazil, with one case was already verified for the disease, while 22 remained as suspicious. The affected cases are members Hokomawë and Momoi sector of the organization Yanomami Hutukara.

The presence of thousands of illegal miners who have invaded the region may be the likely source of the epidemic. Despite repeated warnings, the authorities have not taken the necessary measures to expel them.

In Brazil, at least 23 indigenous patients have gone to a hospital, but most of those affected are unable to access medical assistance, as they live in very remote areas.

Survival International is calling on the authorities in Venezuela to provide immediate medical assistance to these remote communities. Survival's director Stephen Corry said today: "When [indigenous people] suffer from diseases that have never met, many of them die and whole populations can be annihilated. These people are the most vulnerable on the planet. Immediate medical attention is all that will prevent its complete devastation."

[Byline: Antonio Ribeiro]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[This is a very serious situation for the indigenous people who always suffer from introduced pathogens to which they have no prior exposure and consequently, no immunity. Potentially, hundreds of Yanomami could become infected and die if no intervention is taken by the governmental authorities. It is urgent that medical care commence immediately.

The Yanomami are the largest relatively isolated tribe in South America. They live in the rainforests and mountains of northern Brazil and southern Venezuela.

Like most tribes on the continent, they probably migrated across the Bering Straits between Asia and America some 15 000 years ago, making their way slowly down to South America. Today their total population stands at around 35 000.
At over 9.6 million hectares, the Yanomami territory in Brazil is twice the size of Switzerland. In Venezuela, the Yanomami live in the 8.2 million hectare Alto Orinoco - Casiquiare Biosphere Reserve. Together, these areas form the largest forested indigenous territory in the world.

Thousands of gold-miners are now working illegally on Yanomami land, transmitting deadly diseases like malaria and polluting the rivers and forest with mercury. Cattle ranchers are invading and deforesting the eastern fringe of their land. Yanomami health is suffering and critical medical care is not reaching them, especially in Venezuela.

The Brazilian congress is currently debating a bill which, if approved, will permit large-scale mining in indigenous territories. This will be extremely harmful to the Yanomami and other remote tribes in Brazil.

(Excerpted from https://www.survivalinternational.org/tribes/yanomami. Go to URL to read more on the Yanomami and the threat they and their habitat face from the illegal gold mining operations. - Mod.LK]

[Healthmap/ProMED map Brazil https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5895186,6 and Venezuela https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5895186,29]

