[5] Malaysia (Borneo)
Date: Thu 5 Jul 2018
Source: The Borneo Post [edited]
http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/07/05/sia-will-help-prevent-spread-of-measles/


Health officers are urged to carry out massive exercise on the Supplementary Immunisation Activity (SIA) here and in Tatau to prevent the spread of measles. Bintulu Health officer Dr. Norliza Jusoh said the SIA had actually started on [2 Jul 2018] after a measles outbreak was reported here since [13 Apr 2018]. The SIA is a preventive measure which develops herd immunity against the spread of the disease.

"For the record Bintulu has the highest number of measles infection with 179 cases, of which 92 cases were tested positive for measles following lab tests on [3 Jul 2018]," she said during a briefing at the Resident's office here yesterday [Wed 4 Jul 2018].

A total of 171 cases were recorded in Bintulu itself and 8 in Tatau District.

Dr. Norliza said the SIA would be carried out for a month until [31 Jul 2018] as a preventive measure to curb the spread of the disease. She said free door-to-door vaccination from 8am -- 10pm on Mondays to Sundays would involve children aged 6 months -- 15 years old. She added that early detection and treatment was vital in preventing the spread of the disease.

Under the Children National Immunisation Programme, 2 doses of Measles-Mumps-Rubella (MMR) vaccine shots are given to children aged 9 months -- 12 months.

The SIA programme here is divided into 3 areas, namely, Jepak (Week 1) , Sg Plan/ Kidurong (Week 2) and Bintulu (Week 3 and 4). Dr. Norliza said from past experiences, the medical personnel from Bintulu Health Office had encountered difficulties approaching house owners at the residential areas. Many of them did not allow the staff to enter their houses, but asked them to give their children the jabs at the gate under the scorching hot sun.

"For your information, this vaccine is very sensitive to light so it is recommended that it is given in a dim area, even if you don't allow us to enter, it's fine, but not at the gate," Norliza said.

For house owners who might feel unsecured with the presence of the medical staff, she assured them that their personnel would wear the department's uniform and official name tags.

A community leader from Jepak who was present at the meeting has volunteered to join the teams if his service is required.

Bintulu Resident Jack Aman Luat, who chaired the meeting, said the people should not fear the personnel coming to their home for they are doing a very good job in containing the spread of the disease. He also urged the Health Office here to distribute pamphlets to every household in Bintulu to make the people more aware of the disease.

[Byline: Yunus Yussop]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The measles outbreak is due to the high number of children who have never received the full MMR vaccine protocol to protect them from this disease. It is hoped this vaccination campaign will correct the problem. Education on the value of the vaccine is also important for the future generations' protection. - Mod.LK]

